1
00:00:11,160 --> 00:00:13,845
Quite an Arctic storm
blowing out there. Hm!

2
00:00:13,920 --> 00:00:15,922
Come along, Polly,
my child, with my cloak.

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:18,321
Hey, Doctor, you've got
the most fantastic wardrobe.

4
00:00:18,400 --> 00:00:21,483
Yes. We don't know
what we're in for outside there.

5
00:00:21,560 --> 00:00:23,881
Pretty soon we shall be having visitors.

6
00:00:26,280 --> 00:00:27,964
You're different.
You've got no feelings.

7
00:00:28,080 --> 00:00:30,845
I do not understand that word.

8
00:00:30,920 --> 00:00:33,924
Emotions. Love, pride, hate,

9
00:00:34,560 --> 00:00:35,561
fear!

10
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:38,968
Have you no emotions, sir?

11
00:00:40,680 --> 00:00:42,125
What's happened to you, Doctor?

12
00:00:42,240 --> 00:00:46,325
I guess this old body of mine
is wearing a bit thin.

13
00:00:48,720 --> 00:00:51,200
BEN: Doctor. Wakey, wakey.
It's all over now.

14
00:00:56,600 --> 00:00:57,601
No.

15
00:00:58,840 --> 00:01:00,683
It isn't all over.

16
00:01:01,880 --> 00:01:04,565
It's far from being all over.

17
00:01:05,160 --> 00:01:06,161
What are you talking about?

18
00:01:06,240 --> 00:01:09,130
I must get back to the TARDIS.

19
00:01:15,440 --> 00:01:16,930
<i>I can't go through with it.</i>

20
00:01:17,280 --> 00:01:19,647
<i>I will fight it.</i>

21
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:22,604
<i>I will not change.</i>

22
00:01:22,920 --> 00:01:25,161
Hello? Is someone there.

23
00:01:27,120 --> 00:01:28,360
Hello?

24
00:01:33,880 --> 00:01:36,087
- Who is that?
- I'm the Doctor.

25
00:01:37,320 --> 00:01:39,402
Oh, I don't think so.

26
00:01:39,480 --> 00:01:42,370
No. Dear me, no.

27
00:01:43,440 --> 00:01:45,647
You may be a doctor.

28
00:01:45,720 --> 00:01:48,644
But I am the Doctor.

29
00:01:48,720 --> 00:01:52,406
The original, you might say.

30
00:01:55,520 --> 00:01:56,521
You?

31
00:01:59,280 --> 00:02:01,681
How can it be you?

32
00:02:01,760 --> 00:02:04,411
- Do I know you, sir?
- This is the South Pole.

33
00:02:04,520 --> 00:02:05,851
We're at the South Pole.

34
00:02:05,960 --> 00:02:08,281
Of course, we are.
Don't you know that?

35
00:02:08,360 --> 00:02:09,441
This is where it happened.

36
00:02:09,560 --> 00:02:11,483
Where what happened?

37
00:02:11,720 --> 00:02:13,643
This is it.

38
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:17,729
The very first time

39
00:02:18,280 --> 00:02:21,966
that I... Well, you...
We regenerated.

40
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:24,562
You're mid-regeneration, aren't you?

41
00:02:25,520 --> 00:02:28,091
Your face. It's all over the place.

42
00:02:28,440 --> 00:02:30,044
But you're trying to hold it back.

43
00:02:31,120 --> 00:02:33,691
What do you know of regeneration?

44
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:35,286
Are you a Time Lord?

45
00:02:35,360 --> 00:02:36,771
You know who I am. You must.

46
00:02:39,080 --> 00:02:42,562
Have you come to take the ship back?

47
00:02:43,760 --> 00:02:46,843
The ship. You still call it a ship.

48
00:02:46,960 --> 00:02:49,770
Oh, dear.
What have you done to it?

49
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:52,604
Nothing. The windows.

50
00:02:53,160 --> 00:02:55,003
- I don't remember this.
- They're the wrong size!

51
00:02:55,080 --> 00:02:56,730
I don't remember
trying not to change.

52
00:02:56,800 --> 00:02:59,326
- Not back then.
- I'm sure it's changed. Look at it!

53
00:03:00,280 --> 00:03:03,090
It seems to have expanded.

54
00:03:03,160 --> 00:03:05,162
Well, it's all those years
of bigger on the inside.

55
00:03:05,240 --> 00:03:08,449
You try sucking your tummy in that long.
Why are you trying not to regenerate?

56
00:03:08,560 --> 00:03:10,767
I have the courage and the right

57
00:03:10,880 --> 00:03:13,611
to live and die as myself.

58
00:03:13,680 --> 00:03:15,409
Too late. It's started.

59
00:03:16,200 --> 00:03:18,726
A few minutes ago,
you were weak as a kitten, right?

60
00:03:19,240 --> 00:03:23,802
Now, you're fine.
We're in a state of grace, both of us.

61
00:03:23,920 --> 00:03:26,605
But it won't last long.
We have a choice.

62
00:03:27,360 --> 00:03:29,249
Either we change and go on,

63
00:03:30,320 --> 00:03:31,810
or we die as we are.

64
00:03:34,080 --> 00:03:35,366
But, if you...

65
00:03:36,360 --> 00:03:37,521
If you die here...

66
00:03:39,560 --> 00:03:42,211
If your future never happens,

67
00:03:42,280 --> 00:03:44,806
if you don't do the things
that you are supposed to do,

68
00:03:44,920 --> 00:03:46,490
the consequences could be...

69
00:03:49,440 --> 00:03:51,249
- The snow.
- Snow?

70
00:03:51,680 --> 00:03:52,966
Look at it!

71
00:03:54,840 --> 00:03:56,604
How extraordinary.

72
00:04:08,640 --> 00:04:09,801
Everything's stopped.

73
00:04:10,880 --> 00:04:12,006
Why?

74
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:14,286
Maybe it's us.

75
00:04:15,400 --> 00:04:16,686
Maybe it's something else.

76
00:04:17,680 --> 00:04:22,402
But somehow, something
has gone very wrong with time.

77
00:04:22,520 --> 00:04:23,646
MAN: Hello?

78
00:04:27,240 --> 00:04:28,605
Sorry.

79
00:04:29,880 --> 00:04:31,609
I'm so sorry.

80
00:04:32,920 --> 00:04:35,969
I don't suppose
either of you is a doctor?

81
00:04:38,120 --> 00:04:39,121
You trying to be funny?

82
00:05:26,600 --> 00:05:29,126
CAPTAIN: <i>There is
something I should like to say.</i>

83
00:05:29,200 --> 00:05:30,201
<i>That is,</i>

84
00:05:30,600 --> 00:05:33,285
<i>there is something I should
very much like you to understand.</i>

85
00:05:36,960 --> 00:05:40,521
<i>I do not have
the slightest desire to kill you.</i>

86
00:05:41,800 --> 00:05:44,280
<i>The only reason I would do so
is self-defence.</i>

87
00:05:46,120 --> 00:05:50,330
<i>However, since you're aware
I might kill you in self-defence,</i>

88
00:05:50,520 --> 00:05:53,842
<i>there is the strong possibility
you will kill me in self-defence.</i>

89
00:05:56,960 --> 00:06:00,487
It does rather make me wish
you understood English.

90
00:06:04,760 --> 00:06:06,364
Or that I spoke German.

91
00:06:09,680 --> 00:06:11,364
War is hell, eh?

92
00:07:34,560 --> 00:07:37,564
GLASS WOMAN: <i>Time line error.
There is a time line error.</i>

93
00:07:37,640 --> 00:07:38,926
<i>Time line error.</i>

94
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:40,445
<i>There is a time line error.</i>

95
00:07:54,720 --> 00:07:56,210
DOCTOR: Everything stopped.

96
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:58,889
FIRST DOCTOR: But why?

97
00:07:59,200 --> 00:08:00,531
DOCTOR: Maybe it's us.

98
00:08:01,080 --> 00:08:02,650
Maybe it's something else.

99
00:08:03,040 --> 00:08:06,567
But somehow, something has gone
very wrong with time.

100
00:08:06,880 --> 00:08:07,881
Hello.

101
00:08:11,960 --> 00:08:12,961
Sorry.

102
00:08:14,840 --> 00:08:15,966
I'm so sorry.

103
00:08:16,360 --> 00:08:19,443
I don't suppose
either of you is a doctor?

104
00:08:20,560 --> 00:08:21,766
You trying to be funny?

105
00:08:23,880 --> 00:08:25,211
She's coming.

106
00:08:26,120 --> 00:08:28,088
She's coming.

107
00:08:28,160 --> 00:08:29,161
It's her.

108
00:08:31,800 --> 00:08:33,450
FIRST DOCTOR: Not human, I think.

109
00:08:33,760 --> 00:08:37,128
State your planet of origin
and your intentions.

110
00:08:37,280 --> 00:08:40,648
This is Earth,
a level five civilisation.

111
00:08:40,720 --> 00:08:41,960
And it is protected.

112
00:08:42,040 --> 00:08:43,690
It's what?

113
00:08:44,320 --> 00:08:46,641
Oh, okay.
That doesn't usually work.

114
00:08:46,720 --> 00:08:48,529
Protected by whom?

115
00:08:48,680 --> 00:08:51,411
Oh, it is early days. Isn't it?

116
00:08:54,160 --> 00:08:56,811
May I suggest for your own safety,

117
00:08:56,880 --> 00:09:00,089
you step on board my ship?

118
00:09:00,960 --> 00:09:02,121
What ship?

119
00:09:02,200 --> 00:09:04,043
He means, "Get inside the box."

120
00:09:04,120 --> 00:09:07,249
A little snug from this angle.

121
00:09:07,320 --> 00:09:10,449
But you might be in for a surp...

122
00:09:12,680 --> 00:09:13,681
My TARDIS!

123
00:09:14,800 --> 00:09:16,165
Look at my TARDIS!

124
00:09:16,240 --> 00:09:17,765
This is impossible.

125
00:09:17,840 --> 00:09:19,285
Have I been burgled?

126
00:09:19,360 --> 00:09:22,204
- It's... But it's...
- It's hideous.

127
00:09:22,280 --> 00:09:25,204
Bigger on the inside
than it is on the outside.

128
00:09:25,280 --> 00:09:27,009
You know, I thought it probably was.

129
00:09:27,640 --> 00:09:29,369
Glad it's not just me.

130
00:09:30,640 --> 00:09:31,687
What is this place?

131
00:09:31,760 --> 00:09:36,641
This place is, or ought to be,
my TARDIS.

132
00:09:38,080 --> 00:09:40,560
Technically, that is your TARDIS.

133
00:09:40,960 --> 00:09:43,008
It's about 70 feet that way.

134
00:09:43,080 --> 00:09:44,127
See?

135
00:09:44,200 --> 00:09:46,771
Always remember where you parked.
It's gonna come up a lot.

136
00:09:46,840 --> 00:09:48,205
Is this madness?

137
00:09:50,040 --> 00:09:51,166
Am I going mad?

138
00:09:51,440 --> 00:09:55,490
Madness? Well, you're an officer
from World War One at the South Pole

139
00:09:55,560 --> 00:09:57,562
being pursued by an alien
through frozen time.

140
00:09:59,640 --> 00:10:01,244
Madness was never this good.

141
00:10:01,880 --> 00:10:03,086
World War One?

142
00:10:03,760 --> 00:10:05,888
Judging by the uniform, yes.

143
00:10:06,280 --> 00:10:07,566
Yes, but...

144
00:10:08,880 --> 00:10:11,281
What do you mean, "One"?

145
00:10:13,680 --> 00:10:15,330
Oh, sorry, spoilers.

146
00:10:15,440 --> 00:10:16,726
Enough of this.

147
00:10:17,240 --> 00:10:18,401
Who are you?

148
00:10:18,760 --> 00:10:21,081
Um... You know who I am.

149
00:10:21,160 --> 00:10:22,650
You knew the moment you saw me.

150
00:10:22,720 --> 00:10:25,564
I'd say stop being an idiot,
but I kind of know what's coming.

151
00:10:25,800 --> 00:10:31,045
I assure you, I do not have
the faintest idea who you are.

152
00:10:31,120 --> 00:10:33,691
Well, I know who you are.

153
00:10:33,760 --> 00:10:35,842
Is anyone going
to explain what's going on?

154
00:10:37,200 --> 00:10:38,201
DOCTOR: Snap.

155
00:10:43,560 --> 00:10:45,324
You are me.

156
00:10:46,200 --> 00:10:47,690
No. No!

157
00:10:47,760 --> 00:10:50,764
Yes. Yes, I'm very much afraid so.

158
00:10:51,520 --> 00:10:54,967
Do I become you?

159
00:10:55,040 --> 00:10:57,930
Well, there's a few false starts,
but you get there in the end.

160
00:10:58,920 --> 00:11:00,809
But, I thought...

161
00:11:01,400 --> 00:11:02,401
What?

162
00:11:02,480 --> 00:11:07,805
Well, I assumed I'd get younger.

163
00:11:08,280 --> 00:11:09,850
<i>I am younger!</i>

164
00:11:10,400 --> 00:11:14,291
You know, I really don't think
I'm completely following.

165
00:11:14,800 --> 00:11:17,531
- Oh. Oh, dear.
- Oh, you're in shock!

166
00:11:17,600 --> 00:11:19,125
Let me help you.

167
00:11:19,400 --> 00:11:21,004
Brandy.

168
00:11:21,080 --> 00:11:22,684
Get him brandy.
Do you have any?

169
00:11:22,760 --> 00:11:24,649
I had some somewhere.

170
00:11:24,720 --> 00:11:27,041
- Hang on.
- Sit down here, my boy.

171
00:11:27,360 --> 00:11:29,169
Collect your wits.

172
00:11:29,800 --> 00:11:30,961
CAPTAIN: Who are you people?

173
00:11:31,240 --> 00:11:34,767
I am the Doctor and this is my...

174
00:11:34,840 --> 00:11:36,126
It's complicated, actually.

175
00:11:36,200 --> 00:11:38,282
- I am also...
- ...my nurse.

176
00:11:39,920 --> 00:11:40,967
Excuse me?

177
00:11:41,040 --> 00:11:43,850
I realise that seems
a little improbable.

178
00:11:43,920 --> 00:11:45,524
- Yes.
- Because he's a man.

179
00:11:45,600 --> 00:11:46,601
What?

180
00:11:46,680 --> 00:11:50,162
Older gentlemen, like women,
can be put to use.

181
00:11:50,240 --> 00:11:52,368
You can't... You can't
say things like that.

182
00:11:52,440 --> 00:11:53,521
Can't I?

183
00:11:53,840 --> 00:11:54,841
Says who?

184
00:11:54,920 --> 00:11:57,366
Just about everyone you're going to meet
for the rest of your life. Here.

185
00:12:00,800 --> 00:12:02,689
Have you had some of this?

186
00:12:03,080 --> 00:12:06,289
Well, you know,
I may have snuck a glass

187
00:12:06,360 --> 00:12:09,330
at some point in the last 1500 years.

188
00:12:09,400 --> 00:12:11,004
It's been rock and roll.

189
00:12:12,080 --> 00:12:13,366
Here you are.

190
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:16,171
Get this down you.
You'll feel a lot better.

191
00:12:16,240 --> 00:12:17,401
- Thank you.
- Yes.

192
00:12:17,480 --> 00:12:20,245
FIRST DOCTOR: I, erm...
I don't understand any of this.

193
00:12:20,520 --> 00:12:22,329
Well, of course you understand.

194
00:12:22,400 --> 00:12:24,562
I am your future self.

195
00:12:24,800 --> 00:12:26,086
Are you indeed?

196
00:12:26,160 --> 00:12:29,369
And I suppose this is
meant to be my TARDIS?

197
00:12:29,760 --> 00:12:30,761
Our TARDIS.

198
00:12:30,840 --> 00:12:32,251
What's wrong with the lights?

199
00:12:32,400 --> 00:12:33,606
It's supposed to be like this.

200
00:12:33,720 --> 00:12:34,721
Why?

201
00:12:34,840 --> 00:12:35,966
It's atmospheric.

202
00:12:36,320 --> 00:12:39,927
Atmospheric?
This is the flight deck

203
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:43,607
of the most powerful space-time
machine in the known universe,

204
00:12:43,680 --> 00:12:45,842
not a restaurant for the French.

205
00:12:47,440 --> 00:12:49,602
Good Lord. What is that?

206
00:12:49,760 --> 00:12:53,003
Oh. Look what someone
has accidentally left here.

207
00:12:53,080 --> 00:12:56,562
I say!
It's some sort of guitar, isn't it?

208
00:12:56,640 --> 00:12:57,971
- Is it yours?
- No.

209
00:12:58,040 --> 00:13:01,123
It appears to have
been played quite recently.

210
00:13:01,360 --> 00:13:03,647
It's the only thing here
that's been cleaned.

211
00:13:05,200 --> 00:13:08,761
In fact, this whole place
could do with a good dusting.

212
00:13:08,840 --> 00:13:11,684
Obviously, Polly isn't around any more.

213
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:16,127
Please, please.
Please stop saying things like that.

214
00:13:44,240 --> 00:13:45,571
I can't get the engines to start.

215
00:13:47,520 --> 00:13:49,887
There's some kind of signal
blocking the command path.

216
00:13:54,840 --> 00:13:56,126
FEMALE VOICE: <i>Exit your capsule.</i>

217
00:13:56,760 --> 00:13:59,764
<i>The Chamber of the Dead awaits you.</i>

218
00:14:00,480 --> 00:14:02,767
DOCTOR: I'll fix the engines
while you keep her talking.

219
00:14:04,960 --> 00:14:06,200
Fields up.

220
00:14:22,320 --> 00:14:23,845
<i>Look around you.</i>

221
00:14:32,920 --> 00:14:35,571
<i>You stand
in the Chamber of the Dead.</i>

222
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:39,002
<i>You are known to all here</i>

223
00:14:39,600 --> 00:14:42,206
<i>for you are the Doctor of War.</i>

224
00:14:44,400 --> 00:14:45,481
No, no.

225
00:14:45,560 --> 00:14:47,961
The Doctor, yes.

226
00:14:48,040 --> 00:14:53,001
But the Doctor of War?
Never, Ma'am. Never.

227
00:14:54,920 --> 00:14:56,445
<i>We offer you a gift.</i>

228
00:14:56,520 --> 00:14:58,887
<i>Return to us
the human on your TARDIS.</i>

229
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:02,248
<i>And in exchange
you may speak with her again.</i>

230
00:15:02,320 --> 00:15:03,924
Speak with whom?

231
00:15:14,520 --> 00:15:17,649
Young lady, who are you?

232
00:15:20,760 --> 00:15:21,761
Is he here?

233
00:15:22,640 --> 00:15:24,005
Is the Doctor here?

234
00:15:25,880 --> 00:15:27,006
BILL: Doctor!

235
00:15:31,880 --> 00:15:33,120
I knew it!

236
00:15:33,320 --> 00:15:34,651
I did! I knew it!

237
00:15:34,720 --> 00:15:37,530
I knew you couldn't be dead.
You don't have the concentration.

238
00:15:43,120 --> 00:15:44,121
Doctor?

239
00:15:48,160 --> 00:15:49,400
What are you doing?

240
00:15:50,560 --> 00:15:51,925
Just keep still, please.

241
00:15:53,320 --> 00:15:54,560
Bill Potts?

242
00:15:54,880 --> 00:15:55,881
Yeah.

243
00:15:56,640 --> 00:15:59,291
My friend Bill Potts
was turned into a Cyberman.

244
00:16:01,040 --> 00:16:02,246
She gave her life

245
00:16:03,480 --> 00:16:05,767
so that people
she barely knew could live.

246
00:16:06,880 --> 00:16:11,727
So, let's be clear.
Nobody imitates Bill Potts.

247
00:16:11,800 --> 00:16:14,121
Nobody mocks Bill Potts.

248
00:16:15,080 --> 00:16:16,764
Bill Potts

249
00:16:16,840 --> 00:16:18,729
is standing right in front of you.

250
00:16:19,400 --> 00:16:21,164
How is that even possible?

251
00:16:22,840 --> 00:16:25,844
Well, long story short,
I totally pulled.

252
00:16:26,120 --> 00:16:28,691
You did what?

253
00:16:30,040 --> 00:16:32,407
Heather. Do you remember,
the girl in the puddle?

254
00:16:32,560 --> 00:16:34,130
Well, she showed up.

255
00:16:34,200 --> 00:16:35,611
She came for me.

256
00:16:35,720 --> 00:16:36,926
How romantic.

257
00:16:38,240 --> 00:16:39,366
Where is she?

258
00:16:42,280 --> 00:16:43,520
Well, she's...

259
00:16:46,280 --> 00:16:49,045
- She's...
- And how did you get here?

260
00:16:50,080 --> 00:16:51,525
I don't...

261
00:16:52,640 --> 00:16:54,722
- I can't...
- You can't remember. I bet you can't.

262
00:16:57,400 --> 00:17:00,529
That device. What is it?

263
00:17:01,560 --> 00:17:03,050
It's a sonic screwdriver.

264
00:17:03,120 --> 00:17:05,088
A what screwdriver?

265
00:17:06,160 --> 00:17:08,447
It's really a very good job.

266
00:17:08,560 --> 00:17:10,801
An audio screwdriver?

267
00:17:10,920 --> 00:17:13,571
There are only three
low-key markers

268
00:17:14,040 --> 00:17:15,690
indicating that she's a duplicate.

269
00:17:15,800 --> 00:17:17,450
I'm not a duplicate.

270
00:17:17,600 --> 00:17:21,764
So, who has been stealing
the faces of the dead?

271
00:17:41,880 --> 00:17:45,851
Time travel technology, eh? Obviously.

272
00:17:45,920 --> 00:17:47,809
DOCTOR: From the far future.

273
00:17:48,480 --> 00:17:49,970
I know.

274
00:17:54,400 --> 00:17:56,687
- Sunglasses?
- They're sonic.

275
00:17:57,000 --> 00:17:58,365
Indoors?

276
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:07,128
So, what are you?

277
00:18:07,240 --> 00:18:11,040
We are what awaits
at the end of every life.

278
00:18:13,360 --> 00:18:18,366
As every living soul dies,
so we will appear.

279
00:18:18,440 --> 00:18:22,650
We take from you what we need and
return you to the moment of your death.

280
00:18:23,560 --> 00:18:26,609
We are testimony.

281
00:18:30,960 --> 00:18:33,406
DOCTOR: You come
from the distant future?

282
00:18:33,480 --> 00:18:35,847
You travel back in time,
you find people,

283
00:18:35,920 --> 00:18:38,366
at the exact point of death and what?

284
00:18:38,440 --> 00:18:40,807
You harvest something from them?

285
00:18:40,880 --> 00:18:41,881
Yes.

286
00:18:42,560 --> 00:18:46,121
On behalf of the dying,
what is it that we have

287
00:18:46,240 --> 00:18:47,844
that the future needs so badly?

288
00:18:47,920 --> 00:18:51,641
And what is any of this to do
with a World War One Captain

289
00:18:51,720 --> 00:18:55,088
landing at the South Pole
in the wrong decade?

290
00:18:55,160 --> 00:18:59,051
We were returning him to the appointed
time and place of his death.

291
00:18:59,120 --> 00:19:02,920
An error in the time line ejected him
into the wrong time zone.

292
00:19:03,480 --> 00:19:06,802
Now, his death must proceed
as history demands.

293
00:19:07,440 --> 00:19:08,680
If I may.

294
00:19:11,440 --> 00:19:13,249
Who were you?

295
00:19:13,320 --> 00:19:15,561
She wasn't anyone.

296
00:19:15,640 --> 00:19:18,246
She's a computer generated interface

297
00:19:18,440 --> 00:19:21,410
connected to a multiform
inter-phasing...

298
00:19:21,520 --> 00:19:26,208
Oh, for heaven's sake, will you put
that ridiculous buzzing toy away

299
00:19:26,280 --> 00:19:27,884
and look at the woman?

300
00:19:27,960 --> 00:19:30,247
You see? Her face.

301
00:19:30,840 --> 00:19:34,287
It's very slightly asymmetrical.

302
00:19:34,400 --> 00:19:37,927
If it were computer generated,
it wouldn't produce that effect.

303
00:19:38,320 --> 00:19:39,606
Yes!

304
00:19:39,920 --> 00:19:42,241
You're absolutely right.
I should've noticed that.

305
00:19:42,320 --> 00:19:44,687
Well, it might help
if you could see properly.

306
00:19:47,440 --> 00:19:50,762
Excuse me? Doctor?

307
00:19:52,080 --> 00:19:53,366
Get back inside.

308
00:19:53,480 --> 00:19:55,608
I'm not quite sure,

309
00:19:55,720 --> 00:19:57,882
but it seemed to me
that this young lady's life

310
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:00,446
was being offered
in exchange for my own.

311
00:20:00,920 --> 00:20:06,563
Now as it happens, I think my number
is pretty much up anyway.

312
00:20:06,640 --> 00:20:10,167
What are you talking about?
Doctor, what is he talking about?

313
00:20:10,240 --> 00:20:14,040
So, might as well
make it count for something, eh?

314
00:20:14,120 --> 00:20:18,091
I should be happy to take your place
if that would resolve the situation.

315
00:20:18,160 --> 00:20:19,730
GLASS WOMAN: Accepted.

316
00:20:20,880 --> 00:20:23,121
That is...
That is not happening.

317
00:20:23,200 --> 00:20:24,964
That's totally not happening.

318
00:20:26,280 --> 00:20:27,645
Agreed?

319
00:20:27,720 --> 00:20:29,484
Tell me what to do then.

320
00:20:30,080 --> 00:20:32,048
Bill Potts would tell me what to do.

321
00:20:32,120 --> 00:20:33,849
Do what you always do.

322
00:20:35,240 --> 00:20:37,288
Serve at the pleasure of the human race.

323
00:20:41,240 --> 00:20:45,564
Here's what's going to happen.
First, I'm going to escape.

324
00:20:45,640 --> 00:20:47,802
- You, with me.
- Where are we going?

325
00:20:47,880 --> 00:20:49,723
Escape is not possible.

326
00:20:49,800 --> 00:20:52,167
It is possible and it is happening.

327
00:20:52,240 --> 00:20:54,004
And I'm taking Bill
and the Captain with me.

328
00:20:54,080 --> 00:20:56,845
Why are you advertising your intentions?

329
00:20:56,920 --> 00:20:58,922
Can't you stop boasting for a moment?

330
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:00,570
Mr Pastry, too. I could do with a laugh.

331
00:21:00,640 --> 00:21:02,608
GLASS WOMAN: Escape is not possible.

332
00:21:02,680 --> 00:21:05,524
Oh, I'm going to do
way more than escape.

333
00:21:05,600 --> 00:21:08,365
I'm going to find out who you are
and what you are doing,

334
00:21:08,440 --> 00:21:11,683
and if I don't like it, I will come back
and I will stop you.

335
00:21:11,760 --> 00:21:13,603
I will stop all of you.

336
00:21:13,680 --> 00:21:16,047
Who the hell do you think you are?

337
00:21:16,120 --> 00:21:18,851
- The Doctor.
- I am the Doctor.

338
00:21:18,920 --> 00:21:21,810
Who you are, I cannot begin to imagine.

339
00:21:21,880 --> 00:21:23,962
GLASS WOMAN:
Then let us show you, Doctor.

340
00:21:24,040 --> 00:21:26,281
See who you will become.

341
00:21:29,080 --> 00:21:31,890
- DALEK: <i>Doctor!
- Exterminate.</i>

342
00:21:31,960 --> 00:21:34,008
<i>You will be assimilated!</i>

343
00:21:34,080 --> 00:21:35,764
DOCTOR: No, no, no.
That's not a good idea.

344
00:21:35,840 --> 00:21:37,171
They all die.

345
00:21:37,240 --> 00:21:42,167
GLASS WOMAN: The Doctor has walked
in blood through all of time and space.

346
00:21:42,240 --> 00:21:43,969
The Doctor has many names.

347
00:21:44,040 --> 00:21:46,725
MAN: The destroyer of the world!

348
00:21:46,800 --> 00:21:49,326
GLASS WOMAN: The imp of the pandorica.

349
00:21:49,400 --> 00:21:51,289
The shadow of the Valeyard.

350
00:21:51,680 --> 00:21:54,126
The beast of Trenzalore.

351
00:21:54,200 --> 00:21:56,601
The butcher of Skull Moon.

352
00:21:56,680 --> 00:21:58,409
The last tree of Garsennon.

353
00:21:58,480 --> 00:22:00,369
The destroyer of Skate.

354
00:22:00,440 --> 00:22:03,603
He is the Doctor of War.

355
00:22:10,200 --> 00:22:11,884
What... What was that?

356
00:22:11,960 --> 00:22:13,962
To be fair, they cut out all the jokes.

357
00:22:15,640 --> 00:22:17,927
Do what I do when I do it.

358
00:22:23,960 --> 00:22:25,325
Jump!

359
00:22:40,400 --> 00:22:42,129
GLASS WOMAN: They are not escaping!

360
00:23:06,760 --> 00:23:07,761
DOCTOR: Jump!

361
00:23:19,720 --> 00:23:21,722
- BILL: What do we do now?
- Run!

362
00:23:21,800 --> 00:23:23,723
Where? They've got the TARDIS.

363
00:23:23,800 --> 00:23:25,768
Yes. That's exactly
what they're supposed to think.

364
00:23:25,840 --> 00:23:27,365
Yeah, but they do, though. Look.

365
00:23:27,440 --> 00:23:30,489
DOCTOR: They've got my TARDIS.
Over to you, Mary Berry.

366
00:23:30,560 --> 00:23:31,561
Come on.

367
00:23:34,760 --> 00:23:39,129
Doctor, is that another TARDIS?

368
00:23:39,200 --> 00:23:40,611
No.

369
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:43,048
No, it's another of the same TARDIS.

370
00:23:49,560 --> 00:23:51,289
Hang on. The windows are the wrong size.

371
00:23:51,360 --> 00:23:52,805
Inside, quickly.

372
00:23:56,280 --> 00:23:57,281
Take off, now.

373
00:23:57,960 --> 00:23:59,405
Deep space, anywhere.

374
00:24:08,680 --> 00:24:11,331
Tell you what. These police boxes,

375
00:24:11,400 --> 00:24:13,129
they're ever so good, aren't they?

376
00:24:13,200 --> 00:24:15,965
The navigation systems
don't function properly.

377
00:24:16,040 --> 00:24:20,125
I'm unable to programme our flight
with any accuracy.

378
00:24:21,920 --> 00:24:25,970
So, my dear,
I presume you travel with him?

379
00:24:26,240 --> 00:24:28,846
Used to. Kind of miss it.

380
00:24:29,320 --> 00:24:31,800
Well, he clearly misses you.

381
00:24:32,320 --> 00:24:36,211
That ship of his is in dire need
of a good spring clean.

382
00:24:36,280 --> 00:24:38,886
No, no, stop, stop... Look, look.
Oh, look, look, look.

383
00:24:38,960 --> 00:24:40,166
Look at the lovely... The astral map.

384
00:24:40,240 --> 00:24:41,446
Look at the lovely blinking lights.

385
00:24:41,520 --> 00:24:43,249
Look at that.

386
00:24:43,320 --> 00:24:45,084
BILL: He's you.

387
00:24:46,400 --> 00:24:49,449
He is, isn't he? He's you.
He's one of your old faces.

388
00:24:50,640 --> 00:24:54,486
I find I'm lagging behind
a tiny bit again.

389
00:24:55,240 --> 00:24:58,323
Not those again, I forbid it.

390
00:24:58,400 --> 00:25:01,483
There you go. I was right.

391
00:25:01,560 --> 00:25:03,688
- Asymmetrical.
- I said that.

392
00:25:03,760 --> 00:25:05,524
Same difference.

393
00:25:07,760 --> 00:25:11,082
If her face
was based on a human original,

394
00:25:11,160 --> 00:25:12,969
perhaps identifying who that was

395
00:25:13,040 --> 00:25:15,361
will tell us what we need to know
about testimony.

396
00:25:15,440 --> 00:25:17,966
Er, why am I wearing these?

397
00:25:18,040 --> 00:25:19,485
Because I love it.

398
00:25:19,560 --> 00:25:21,528
Never take those off.

399
00:25:21,600 --> 00:25:23,011
What's "browser history"?

400
00:25:24,640 --> 00:25:28,486
I'm trying to match her face
in the TARDIS databank.

401
00:25:29,080 --> 00:25:31,048
But there's hardly anything in it yet.

402
00:25:31,120 --> 00:25:33,248
We need a bigger database.

403
00:25:33,840 --> 00:25:36,411
Possibly the Matrix on Gallifrey.

404
00:25:38,160 --> 00:25:42,051
No. We need something bigger
than the Matrix.

405
00:25:42,600 --> 00:25:46,366
CAPTAIN: <i>So, basically we 're trying
to track the Glass Lady, yes?</i>

406
00:25:46,440 --> 00:25:49,762
BILL: <i>Basically.</i>
FIRST DOCTOR: <i>A striking creature.</i>

407
00:25:53,000 --> 00:25:55,048
Quite beautiful really, isn't she?

408
00:25:55,120 --> 00:25:58,363
Yeah, if you like ladies made of glass.

409
00:25:58,440 --> 00:26:02,843
Well, aren't all ladies
made of glass in a way?

410
00:26:04,480 --> 00:26:06,721
Very good, sir, very good.

411
00:26:06,800 --> 00:26:08,290
Are we now?

412
00:26:08,920 --> 00:26:11,924
Oh, my dear,
I hope it doesn't offend you to know

413
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:16,562
that I have had some experience
of the, er, fairer sex.

414
00:26:16,640 --> 00:26:18,324
Me too.

415
00:26:20,280 --> 00:26:21,486
Good Lord.

416
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:30,331
Where are we?

417
00:26:30,400 --> 00:26:34,166
FIRST DOCTOR: But you steered the ship,
you piloted her perfectly.

418
00:26:34,240 --> 00:26:37,961
We are at
the very centre of the universe.

419
00:26:38,040 --> 00:26:40,042
DOCTOR: Out there is the most
comprehensive database

420
00:26:40,120 --> 00:26:41,121
of all life anywhere.

421
00:26:43,600 --> 00:26:45,409
There is just one little problem.

422
00:26:45,480 --> 00:26:47,244
Which is?

423
00:26:47,400 --> 00:26:48,845
It wants to kill me.

424
00:27:03,440 --> 00:27:05,283
The Weapon Forges of Villengard.

425
00:27:05,360 --> 00:27:07,283
Once the nightmare
of the seven galaxies.

426
00:27:08,400 --> 00:27:11,927
Now home to the dispossessed.

427
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:14,890
I say, I think there's something
moving over here.

428
00:27:14,960 --> 00:27:16,962
Step away, please.

429
00:27:17,040 --> 00:27:18,326
Probably just rats.

430
00:27:18,760 --> 00:27:20,410
I'm used to rats.

431
00:27:28,600 --> 00:27:31,171
Deep breaths, deep breaths.

432
00:27:31,240 --> 00:27:32,730
Just breathe, Captain, you'll be fine.

433
00:27:32,800 --> 00:27:35,041
FIRST DOCTOR: That creature,
it looked familiar.

434
00:27:35,120 --> 00:27:37,930
It's mutated a bit, but, yes,
I should think it did.

435
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:40,446
Come along, my dear chap,
you'll be fine.

436
00:27:40,520 --> 00:27:43,410
- Get him into the TARDIS.
- What are those things?

437
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:46,843
DOCTOR: Er...

438
00:27:50,040 --> 00:27:51,280
What we came here for.

439
00:27:52,280 --> 00:27:55,011
The biggest database in the galaxy.

440
00:27:55,080 --> 00:27:56,320
They'll settle down in a moment.

441
00:27:57,920 --> 00:28:02,482
So, do we talk to them?
Ask them questions? How does it work?

442
00:28:02,560 --> 00:28:04,881
We don't do anything, I do.

443
00:28:04,960 --> 00:28:06,769
- No, no, no...
- You're going to wait in the TARDIS.

444
00:28:06,840 --> 00:28:09,650
- But why?
- You need to look after the Captain.

445
00:28:09,840 --> 00:28:13,367
You're lying.
You think I'm a duplicate. A trick.

446
00:28:13,520 --> 00:28:16,330
I don't know what I think.

447
00:28:16,400 --> 00:28:19,927
But if there's the slightest chance
that Bill Potts is alive,

448
00:28:21,240 --> 00:28:25,962
and standing in front of me,
then I will not under any circumstances,

449
00:28:26,120 --> 00:28:27,645
put her life in danger again.

450
00:28:27,840 --> 00:28:31,925
Seriously? You're looking right at me
and you don't even know I'm here?

451
00:28:32,560 --> 00:28:35,530
Correct. I ask you to respect that.

452
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:37,684
- And respect me.
- You're an arse.

453
00:28:37,960 --> 00:28:42,124
You're a stupid bloody arse.

454
00:28:42,320 --> 00:28:44,402
As I've always respected you.

455
00:28:46,760 --> 00:28:50,287
If I hear any more language
like that from you, young lady,

456
00:28:50,360 --> 00:28:53,091
you're in for
a jolly good smacked bottom.

457
00:28:59,640 --> 00:29:01,404
Can we just pretend that
that never happened?

458
00:29:01,480 --> 00:29:02,925
I'm a broad-minded girl.

459
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:06,800
I mean, I know we have this whole
professor/student thing going on...

460
00:29:06,880 --> 00:29:09,451
Can we just never ever
talk about this again?

461
00:29:09,560 --> 00:29:11,528
Yeah, I hope we talk about it loads.

462
00:29:13,960 --> 00:29:17,760
I hope we spend years
laughing about it.

463
00:29:24,360 --> 00:29:25,486
Come back alive.

464
00:29:25,680 --> 00:29:26,920
Be here when I do.

465
00:29:34,720 --> 00:29:38,247
Perhaps another nip of brandy.

466
00:29:39,320 --> 00:29:43,211
Mmm. So that's where it went.

467
00:29:45,240 --> 00:29:46,969
I'll look after him.

468
00:29:47,080 --> 00:29:49,242
Good girl. Quite right.

469
00:29:49,320 --> 00:29:53,370
Now, young lady,
I don't want to have to repeat myself.

470
00:29:53,440 --> 00:29:55,283
I don't think any of us want that.

471
00:29:55,440 --> 00:29:57,442
I'll see you both presently.

472
00:29:59,920 --> 00:30:01,206
Brandy?

473
00:30:01,640 --> 00:30:02,880
Please.

474
00:30:17,320 --> 00:30:20,403
FIRST DOCTOR:
These creatures, what are they?

475
00:30:20,640 --> 00:30:22,005
DOCTOR: Old friends of ours.

476
00:30:22,560 --> 00:30:24,369
But they've
really come out of their shell.

477
00:30:24,440 --> 00:30:26,204
FIRST DOCTOR: Out of their shell?

478
00:30:26,720 --> 00:30:27,767
You all right?

479
00:30:30,560 --> 00:30:33,040
I'll be... I'll be fine in a moment.

480
00:30:33,280 --> 00:30:34,645
Well, what's the matter?

481
00:30:34,720 --> 00:30:37,371
I died a few hours ago
then I refused to regenerate.

482
00:30:37,440 --> 00:30:39,761
It catches up with you.
You know, it's like a big lunch.

483
00:30:39,840 --> 00:30:41,763
I did exactly the same.

484
00:30:42,320 --> 00:30:43,731
I know you did. But why?

485
00:30:44,760 --> 00:30:46,046
I don't remember this.

486
00:30:46,760 --> 00:30:48,603
Why are you refusing the regeneration?

487
00:30:48,680 --> 00:30:49,806
Fear.

488
00:30:51,040 --> 00:30:53,441
I'm afraid. Very, very afraid.

489
00:30:54,640 --> 00:30:57,246
I don't normally admit that
to, er, anyone else.

490
00:30:58,320 --> 00:31:00,607
Don't worry.
Technically you still haven't.

491
00:31:02,200 --> 00:31:03,247
Why are you?

492
00:31:10,200 --> 00:31:11,884
FIRST DOCTOR: There's something
in that tower!

493
00:31:14,120 --> 00:31:15,326
DOCTOR: Must be my friend.

494
00:31:16,040 --> 00:31:18,042
FIRST DOCTOR:
Why do you call it your friend?

495
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:22,809
DOCTOR: He's got a great big gun.

496
00:31:23,160 --> 00:31:25,128
Are you suggesting I insult him?

497
00:31:28,280 --> 00:31:29,486
Just scan me.

498
00:31:30,280 --> 00:31:32,009
Go on, scan me.

499
00:31:33,160 --> 00:31:34,764
'Cause I've got big news for you.

500
00:31:35,600 --> 00:31:37,090
I'm dying!

501
00:31:45,960 --> 00:31:47,246
See, it's true.

502
00:31:49,640 --> 00:31:50,641
Dying.

503
00:31:52,640 --> 00:31:56,850
Now, be honest with yourself,
wouldn't you like to see that up close?

504
00:32:06,200 --> 00:32:08,202
Come on, up and at 'em,
Corporal Jones.

505
00:32:08,280 --> 00:32:09,441
I don't know.

506
00:32:12,520 --> 00:32:13,567
Funny thing,

507
00:32:14,840 --> 00:32:16,444
I wasn't afraid in the crater.

508
00:32:18,280 --> 00:32:19,805
One doesn't want to die, of course,

509
00:32:19,880 --> 00:32:21,530
but one gets in a certain frame of mind,

510
00:32:21,600 --> 00:32:24,604
one pulls oneself together
and gets on with the matter in hand.

511
00:32:27,120 --> 00:32:29,964
Big shock for everyone.
Back in Cromer of course.

512
00:32:30,320 --> 00:32:32,527
BILL: You have family?

513
00:32:32,600 --> 00:32:34,364
My wife will miss me.

514
00:32:35,720 --> 00:32:37,722
That's perfectly natural.

515
00:32:38,160 --> 00:32:40,208
But she's a solid woman,
remarkably solid.

516
00:32:40,280 --> 00:32:41,884
And my boys...

517
00:32:43,520 --> 00:32:44,760
Well...

518
00:32:45,800 --> 00:32:48,724
Sons are supposed to
move on from their fathers.

519
00:32:48,800 --> 00:32:50,040
It's the proper way.

520
00:32:50,560 --> 00:32:52,130
BILL: Of course.

521
00:32:53,000 --> 00:32:54,729
Trouble is, I thought I'd been rescued.

522
00:32:55,640 --> 00:32:58,246
Felt rather like a miracle, in fact.

523
00:33:00,960 --> 00:33:03,281
But I do have this feeling
they're going to put me back.

524
00:33:04,160 --> 00:33:05,400
Back in that crater.

525
00:33:06,480 --> 00:33:07,925
In time to die.

526
00:33:09,040 --> 00:33:10,405
And you see,

527
00:33:11,560 --> 00:33:13,085
I'm not ready any more.

528
00:33:14,760 --> 00:33:16,285
I've lost the idea of it.

529
00:33:18,680 --> 00:33:20,170
That's the trouble with hope.

530
00:33:21,960 --> 00:33:23,485
Makes one awfully frightened.

531
00:33:26,200 --> 00:33:28,771
I must sound like
the most dreadful coward.

532
00:33:38,600 --> 00:33:41,001
Okay, I'd better go up alone.

533
00:33:41,080 --> 00:33:42,764
I won't hear of it.

534
00:33:44,520 --> 00:33:48,161
That thing up there
won't miss the chance to kill me twice.

535
00:33:48,240 --> 00:33:50,242
The paradox would
rip the universe apart.

536
00:33:51,040 --> 00:33:54,203
And you know how much hard work it is
putting it back together again.

537
00:33:54,280 --> 00:33:56,442
You keep a lookout down here.

538
00:33:56,520 --> 00:33:58,443
Oh, if you insist.

539
00:34:43,560 --> 00:34:45,927
You know what? You're
a bit of a legend these days.

540
00:34:47,520 --> 00:34:49,329
Not everyone believes it.

541
00:34:54,720 --> 00:34:57,644
People don't think that it could happen.

542
00:34:58,880 --> 00:35:02,327
Someone like you could
turn against your own kind.

543
00:35:02,400 --> 00:35:04,482
Because your kind don't do that.

544
00:35:05,840 --> 00:35:07,524
Out of their shells.

545
00:35:11,520 --> 00:35:13,409
Because people don't believe

546
00:35:14,400 --> 00:35:16,243
there could be any such thing

547
00:35:19,640 --> 00:35:21,165
as a good Dalek.

548
00:35:23,640 --> 00:35:25,881
<i>I am not a good Dalek!</i>

549
00:35:25,960 --> 00:35:28,008
<i>You are a good Dalek!</i>

550
00:35:32,040 --> 00:35:34,441
Oh. Hello, my dear.

551
00:35:34,920 --> 00:35:37,844
Now, Rusty, you know that I'm dying.

552
00:35:38,560 --> 00:35:41,325
If you don't want me to go off and die
somewhere else where you can't watch,

553
00:35:41,400 --> 00:35:43,289
you're gonna have to
stop shooting at me.

554
00:35:45,120 --> 00:35:47,964
<i>I agree to your terms.</i>

555
00:35:48,320 --> 00:35:50,084
Well, I'm going to need some proof.

556
00:36:00,600 --> 00:36:01,806
You know what?

557
00:36:01,880 --> 00:36:04,451
You're the very first Dalek
that ever got naked for me.

558
00:36:05,880 --> 00:36:08,884
You're the first one, yeah,
like the original version of the Doctor?

559
00:36:08,960 --> 00:36:11,042
My dear, you should
get back to the ship.

560
00:36:11,120 --> 00:36:12,565
This place isn't safe.

561
00:36:12,640 --> 00:36:14,642
You're the one who stole the TARDIS
and ran away.

562
00:36:14,720 --> 00:36:17,087
The Captain might be needing you.

563
00:36:17,160 --> 00:36:19,447
No, the Captain's fine.
Why did you do it?

564
00:36:19,520 --> 00:36:23,241
Oh, I'm sure your Doctor has explained.

565
00:36:24,760 --> 00:36:26,489
Not even sure he remembers.

566
00:36:26,560 --> 00:36:29,564
There were many pressing reasons.

567
00:36:30,240 --> 00:36:33,881
I don't mean what you ran away from.
What were you running to?

568
00:36:36,440 --> 00:36:38,363
That's rather a good question.

569
00:36:38,880 --> 00:36:40,325
Questions are kind of my thing.

570
00:36:41,640 --> 00:36:42,880
How are you with answers?

571
00:36:43,600 --> 00:36:45,011
Been a long time.

572
00:36:46,200 --> 00:36:47,850
Remember the good old days?

573
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:50,890
When I got miniaturised
and climbed around inside you?

574
00:36:51,600 --> 00:36:55,161
<i>You taught me to hate the Daleks.</i>

575
00:36:56,040 --> 00:36:57,326
Billions of years ago.

576
00:36:57,400 --> 00:36:58,925
What have you been up to since then?

577
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:00,809
<i>Destroying Daleks.</i>

578
00:37:00,880 --> 00:37:03,565
Yes, all the ones who come here
to murder you, yes.

579
00:37:03,640 --> 00:37:05,369
I saw the mess outside.

580
00:37:05,440 --> 00:37:07,169
<i>Why are you here?</i>

581
00:37:09,760 --> 00:37:11,922
As a Dalek,

582
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:15,971
you are linked
in to the Dalek hive mind.

583
00:37:16,040 --> 00:37:17,724
All Daleks are.

584
00:37:18,920 --> 00:37:20,445
Biggest database I know.

585
00:37:21,080 --> 00:37:22,320
I'd like to access it.

586
00:37:22,720 --> 00:37:25,530
<i>Why would I help you?</i>

587
00:37:27,080 --> 00:37:32,371
Because helping me in any way

588
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:35,490
does something wonderful.

589
00:37:39,240 --> 00:37:41,208
It hurts the Daleks.

590
00:37:42,440 --> 00:37:45,284
FIRST DOCTOR:
There is good and there is evil.

591
00:37:46,320 --> 00:37:49,324
I left Gallifrey
to answer a question of my own.

592
00:37:49,720 --> 00:37:53,486
By any analysis, evil should always win.

593
00:37:54,360 --> 00:37:58,490
Good is not
a practical survival strategy.

594
00:37:59,240 --> 00:38:01,891
It requires loyalty,

595
00:38:02,520 --> 00:38:05,364
self-sacrifice and, er, love.

596
00:38:05,960 --> 00:38:10,090
And so, why does good prevail?

597
00:38:10,480 --> 00:38:12,721
What keeps the balance
between good and evil

598
00:38:12,800 --> 00:38:15,326
in this appalling universe?

599
00:38:16,720 --> 00:38:20,884
Is there some kind of logic,
some mysterious force?

600
00:38:21,760 --> 00:38:24,240
Perhaps there's just a bloke.

601
00:38:26,240 --> 00:38:28,322
- A bloke?
- Yeah.

602
00:38:28,800 --> 00:38:33,203
Perhaps there's just some bloke
wandering around

603
00:38:33,280 --> 00:38:35,009
putting everything right
when it goes wrong.

604
00:38:35,440 --> 00:38:38,444
Well, that would be a nice story,
wouldn't it?

605
00:38:38,520 --> 00:38:39,726
That would be the best.

606
00:38:39,800 --> 00:38:42,883
But the real world is not a fairytale.

607
00:38:43,560 --> 00:38:45,767
You dash around the universe

608
00:38:45,840 --> 00:38:47,569
trying to figure out
what's holding it all together

609
00:38:47,640 --> 00:38:50,849
and you really, really don't know.

610
00:38:51,480 --> 00:38:53,050
You know me in the future.

611
00:38:53,120 --> 00:38:55,122
Do I ever understand?

612
00:38:55,960 --> 00:38:56,961
No.

613
00:38:58,800 --> 00:39:00,450
I really don't think you do.

614
00:39:03,640 --> 00:39:05,483
Everyone who's ever met you does.

615
00:39:07,680 --> 00:39:09,125
You're amazing, Doctor.

616
00:39:10,160 --> 00:39:11,321
Never forget that.

617
00:39:12,080 --> 00:39:13,764
Never ever.

618
00:39:14,880 --> 00:39:17,724
Well, that's very kind of you.

619
00:39:17,800 --> 00:39:20,485
We just needed to
understand you, Doctor.

620
00:39:23,760 --> 00:39:25,683
"Professor Helen Clay."

621
00:39:25,760 --> 00:39:30,209
"University of New Earth,
year 5 billion and 12."

622
00:39:32,600 --> 00:39:34,841
There's footage, can you run it?

623
00:39:35,880 --> 00:39:37,041
A spy.

624
00:39:38,560 --> 00:39:39,846
A spy in the camp.

625
00:39:39,920 --> 00:39:41,251
No, not a spy.

626
00:39:43,040 --> 00:39:44,280
I'm Bill Potts.

627
00:39:44,920 --> 00:39:47,685
But I'm part of Testimony now.

628
00:39:49,600 --> 00:39:53,650
The Testimony Foundation combines
the resources of time travel

629
00:39:53,720 --> 00:39:57,281
with the latest
in memory extraction techniques.

630
00:39:57,920 --> 00:40:01,686
The near dead can be lifted momentarily
from their time streams,

631
00:40:01,800 --> 00:40:03,643
their memories duplicated,

632
00:40:03,720 --> 00:40:08,248
and then their physical souls returned
to the moment of their dissolution,

633
00:40:08,360 --> 00:40:12,763
without pain, distress
or any recall of the process.

634
00:40:14,000 --> 00:40:17,925
Now the dead can speak again.

635
00:40:18,600 --> 00:40:20,648
We can hear the testimony

636
00:40:20,720 --> 00:40:22,324
of the past.

637
00:40:22,560 --> 00:40:24,528
And channelled through
our glass avatars,

638
00:40:24,600 --> 00:40:27,763
they can walk among us again.

639
00:40:28,040 --> 00:40:31,840
This is Heaven on New Earth.

640
00:40:34,040 --> 00:40:35,769
It's not an evil plan.

641
00:40:36,840 --> 00:40:39,764
I don't really know what to do
when it isn't an evil plan.

642
00:40:41,160 --> 00:40:43,845
Why did you stop it? Rusty?

643
00:40:45,800 --> 00:40:49,805
He didn't stop it.
They've frozen time again.

644
00:40:50,080 --> 00:40:51,081
Who has?

645
00:40:56,280 --> 00:40:57,884
Not everything's evil, Doctor.

646
00:40:59,160 --> 00:41:01,049
You're not the only kind one
in the universe.

647
00:41:01,120 --> 00:41:02,121
I knew you weren't real.

648
00:41:02,520 --> 00:41:05,330
Oh, shut up and stop being so stupid!
Of course I'm real.

649
00:41:05,960 --> 00:41:08,531
What is anyone supposed to be
except a bunch of memories?

650
00:41:09,440 --> 00:41:13,411
These are my memories,
so this is me. I'm Bill Potts.

651
00:41:13,520 --> 00:41:14,806
And I'm back.

652
00:41:15,520 --> 00:41:17,124
And so long as I'm here,

653
00:41:18,240 --> 00:41:21,767
what the hell do you mean
you're not going to regenerate?

654
00:41:25,160 --> 00:41:26,730
There has to be an end, Bill.

655
00:41:27,200 --> 00:41:29,521
For everyone, everywhere.

656
00:41:30,840 --> 00:41:32,080
What about the Captain?

657
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:37,288
You know he has to die at his allotted
point in time and space.

658
00:41:38,320 --> 00:41:40,049
To correct the error.

659
00:41:41,400 --> 00:41:43,641
I'm so tired of losing people.

660
00:41:45,440 --> 00:41:47,761
If the Captain has to die,

661
00:41:47,960 --> 00:41:50,930
a request... This was our fault.

662
00:41:51,160 --> 00:41:52,161
How so?

663
00:41:53,480 --> 00:41:54,970
Let us take him back.

664
00:41:55,320 --> 00:41:57,687
FIRST DOCTOR: <i>How was this our fault?</i>
DOCTOR: <i>You and me</i>

665
00:41:58,000 --> 00:42:00,480
<i>tried to die twice
in the same lifetime.</i>

666
00:42:01,280 --> 00:42:04,682
<i>Our lives are woven
throughout time and space.</i>

667
00:42:05,200 --> 00:42:08,841
<i>We caused the time line error
that put the Captain in the wrong place.</i>

668
00:42:09,000 --> 00:42:11,606
<i>We created a whirlpool in time</i>

669
00:42:11,840 --> 00:42:13,569
<i>that landed him at our feet.</i>

670
00:42:13,840 --> 00:42:18,004
<i>But why him? What's so important
about one captain?</i>

671
00:42:19,800 --> 00:42:21,962
Everybody is important to somebody,

672
00:42:23,240 --> 00:42:24,571
somewhere.

673
00:42:25,880 --> 00:42:27,245
Are you all right?

674
00:42:28,320 --> 00:42:30,448
Yes, I'm fine. Absolutely.

675
00:42:31,120 --> 00:42:32,246
Just thinking.

676
00:42:33,600 --> 00:42:35,409
I told the wife
I'd be home for Christmas.

677
00:42:36,960 --> 00:42:39,088
Funny how things work out.

678
00:43:05,520 --> 00:43:06,965
Thank you.

679
00:43:11,400 --> 00:43:14,529
Thank you, all.
You've all been most gracious

680
00:43:14,600 --> 00:43:16,204
under the unfortunate circumstances.

681
00:43:16,440 --> 00:43:18,568
I regret, Captain,

682
00:43:18,640 --> 00:43:21,484
that the universe generally

683
00:43:21,560 --> 00:43:24,131
fails to be a fairytale.

684
00:43:24,440 --> 00:43:27,284
When time resumes,
you will not remember this.

685
00:43:27,360 --> 00:43:30,569
A perception filter
will also render us invisible.

686
00:43:31,760 --> 00:43:33,125
Yes.

687
00:43:33,200 --> 00:43:35,441
One imagines some
of those words were attached

688
00:43:35,560 --> 00:43:37,449
to actual meanings of some sort.

689
00:43:38,240 --> 00:43:41,164
One thing you could possibly
do for me if you're very kind?

690
00:43:41,720 --> 00:43:44,690
Oh, anything. Name it.

691
00:43:44,760 --> 00:43:47,764
My family. Perhaps you could

692
00:43:47,840 --> 00:43:49,968
look in on them
from time to time.

693
00:43:50,320 --> 00:43:52,687
We should be delighted...

694
00:43:52,760 --> 00:43:55,331
- What's the name?
- Lethbridge-Stewart.

695
00:43:56,240 --> 00:43:58,766
Captain Archibald Hamish.

696
00:43:58,880 --> 00:44:00,245
Lethbridge-Stewart.

697
00:44:00,320 --> 00:44:02,368
FIRST DOCTOR:
I shall make it my business.

698
00:44:03,440 --> 00:44:06,649
You can trust him on that.

699
00:44:07,280 --> 00:44:08,520
Thank you so much.

700
00:44:09,360 --> 00:44:11,806
I believe I am now ready.

701
00:44:34,480 --> 00:44:36,130
Cold, isn't it?

702
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:40,684
It's about to get colder, I suppose.

703
00:44:41,440 --> 00:44:42,487
For one of us.

704
00:45:02,680 --> 00:45:03,966
I say...

705
00:45:06,040 --> 00:45:07,121
Is that singing?

706
00:45:26,200 --> 00:45:27,531
Is that...

707
00:45:28,120 --> 00:45:29,610
Christmas carols?

708
00:45:31,600 --> 00:45:34,888
♪ <i> Silent night</i> ♪

709
00:45:35,520 --> 00:45:39,047
♪ <i> Holy night</i> ♪

710
00:45:39,720 --> 00:45:43,486
♪ <i> All is calm</i> ♪

711
00:45:43,720 --> 00:45:47,327
♪ <i> All is bright</i> ♪

712
00:45:48,080 --> 00:45:51,880
♪ <i> Round yon virgin</i> ♪

713
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:53,126
♪ <i> Mother and child </i> ♪

714
00:45:53,200 --> 00:45:55,248
You know, I could swear
it's coming from both sides.

715
00:45:56,080 --> 00:45:59,926
If I've got my timings right,
and clearly I have,

716
00:46:00,240 --> 00:46:02,322
then we should be
right at the beginning.

717
00:46:02,400 --> 00:46:03,526
SOLDIER: Hold your fire.

718
00:46:03,600 --> 00:46:05,887
DOCTOR: I adjusted the time frame
only by a couple of hours.

719
00:46:05,960 --> 00:46:07,644
Any other day, it wouldn't
make any difference

720
00:46:07,760 --> 00:46:10,206
but this is Christmas 1914,

721
00:46:10,480 --> 00:46:13,802
and a human miracle
is about to happen.

722
00:46:14,800 --> 00:46:16,928
The Christmas armistice.

723
00:46:28,680 --> 00:46:30,250
Wounded man here!

724
00:46:32,720 --> 00:46:34,484
Wounded man here!

725
00:46:34,560 --> 00:46:36,130
Wounded man.

726
00:46:38,840 --> 00:46:40,365
DOCTOR: <i>Never happened again,</i>

727
00:46:40,480 --> 00:46:42,881
<i>any war, anywhere.</i>

728
00:46:42,960 --> 00:46:45,531
I say, wounded man here.

729
00:46:45,640 --> 00:46:47,130
Wounded man!

730
00:46:47,600 --> 00:46:49,329
DOCTOR: <i>But for one day,</i>

731
00:46:50,200 --> 00:46:53,807
<i>one Christmas,
a very long time ago,</i>

732
00:46:55,080 --> 00:46:57,447
<i>everyone just put down their weapons</i>

733
00:46:58,320 --> 00:47:00,209
<i>and started to sing.</i>

734
00:47:01,600 --> 00:47:03,364
<i>Everybody just stopped.</i>

735
00:47:04,880 --> 00:47:06,450
Everyone.

736
00:47:07,200 --> 00:47:08,804
It was just kind.

737
00:47:09,200 --> 00:47:11,407
FIRST DOCTOR: You've saved him.

738
00:47:12,560 --> 00:47:14,130
DOCTOR: Both of them.

739
00:47:14,680 --> 00:47:16,091
Never hurts.

740
00:47:16,240 --> 00:47:18,481
A couple fewer
dead people on the battlefield.

741
00:47:22,240 --> 00:47:25,642
So that's what it means
to be a Doctor

742
00:47:25,960 --> 00:47:27,769
of War.

743
00:47:28,560 --> 00:47:30,369
You were right, you know.

744
00:47:30,440 --> 00:47:33,649
The universe generally
fails to be a fairytale.

745
00:47:36,400 --> 00:47:37,890
But that's where we come in.

746
00:47:44,200 --> 00:47:46,487
♪ <i> For auld lang syne, my dear</i> ♪

747
00:47:46,720 --> 00:47:49,883
♪ <i> For auld lang syne</i> ♪

748
00:47:50,760 --> 00:47:54,446
♪ <i> We'll take a cup of kindness yet</i> ♪

749
00:47:54,800 --> 00:47:57,849
♪ <i> For auld lang syne</i> ♪

750
00:47:58,480 --> 00:48:02,326
♪ <i> For auld lang syne, my dear</i> ♪

751
00:48:02,600 --> 00:48:06,002
♪ <i> For auld lang syne</i> ♪

752
00:48:06,400 --> 00:48:10,166
♪ <i> We'll take a cup of kindness yet</i> ♪

753
00:48:10,480 --> 00:48:13,211
♪ <i> For auld lang syne </i> ♪

754
00:48:13,280 --> 00:48:15,248
I think I'm ready now.

755
00:48:15,640 --> 00:48:17,847
But I should like to know...

756
00:48:19,200 --> 00:48:20,850
Are you?

757
00:48:21,520 --> 00:48:23,045
You'll find out.

758
00:48:24,040 --> 00:48:25,326
The long way round.

759
00:48:25,800 --> 00:48:27,370
Whatever you decide,

760
00:48:28,600 --> 00:48:30,887
good luck, Doctor.

761
00:48:33,000 --> 00:48:34,650
Goodbye, Doctor.

762
00:49:29,560 --> 00:49:31,244
Well then...

763
00:49:33,320 --> 00:49:34,924
Here we go.

764
00:49:35,920 --> 00:49:38,241
The long way round.

765
00:50:13,280 --> 00:50:14,691
BILL: Are you okay?

766
00:50:19,480 --> 00:50:21,323
Shall we go for one last stroll,

767
00:50:22,120 --> 00:50:23,531
Miss Potts?

768
00:50:33,720 --> 00:50:36,007
You know what the hardest thing
about knowing you was?

769
00:50:37,440 --> 00:50:38,885
My superior intelligence.

770
00:50:39,560 --> 00:50:43,531
Bedazzling charisma...
Oh, my impeccable dress sense.

771
00:50:43,800 --> 00:50:45,325
Letting you go...

772
00:50:49,160 --> 00:50:52,926
Letting go of the Doctor
is so, so hard.

773
00:50:54,320 --> 00:50:55,685
Isn't it?

774
00:50:56,240 --> 00:51:00,006
You see, that's... That's not the sort
of thing the real Bill Potts would say.

775
00:51:00,400 --> 00:51:02,368
I am the real Bill!

776
00:51:02,520 --> 00:51:04,921
A life is just memories.
I'm all her memories.

777
00:51:05,480 --> 00:51:07,687
- So I'm her.
- If you say so.

778
00:51:07,960 --> 00:51:11,407
Okay, I'm gonna prove to you
how important memories are.

779
00:51:11,480 --> 00:51:13,084
I've got a little goodbye present
for you.

780
00:51:13,160 --> 00:51:15,731
Oh, that's nice. Will I have to pretend
to like it, because

781
00:51:15,800 --> 00:51:18,007
- honestly, that rug...
- Oh, come here, you.

782
00:51:24,400 --> 00:51:25,970
Merry Christmas, Doctor.

783
00:51:30,760 --> 00:51:32,000
Clara.

784
00:51:32,640 --> 00:51:33,721
Hello.

785
00:51:34,920 --> 00:51:36,285
You stupid old man.

786
00:51:36,920 --> 00:51:38,160
You're back.

787
00:51:39,360 --> 00:51:40,964
You're in my head.

788
00:51:43,680 --> 00:51:45,364
All my memories...

789
00:51:47,880 --> 00:51:49,006
are back.

790
00:51:49,360 --> 00:51:51,328
And don't go
forgetting me again, because...

791
00:51:53,120 --> 00:51:54,645
quite frankly, that was offensive.

792
00:51:57,080 --> 00:51:59,731
Memories. They're important, right?

793
00:51:59,800 --> 00:52:01,962
I know what you're thinking.

794
00:52:02,040 --> 00:52:03,530
Where is he?

795
00:52:04,080 --> 00:52:05,241
Hello, sir.

796
00:52:05,360 --> 00:52:06,771
When you're already dying

797
00:52:06,880 --> 00:52:09,326
you're entitled to think that your day
couldn't get any worse, but...

798
00:52:09,800 --> 00:52:11,370
here you are.

799
00:52:11,440 --> 00:52:13,841
And both of you are here.
How does that work?

800
00:52:14,800 --> 00:52:16,245
We can be everyone.

801
00:52:16,360 --> 00:52:17,805
- We are everyone.
- Mmm-hmm.

802
00:52:18,280 --> 00:52:19,520
Yes, good this, innit?

803
00:52:19,640 --> 00:52:22,120
Now I'm all made of glass,
not just my nipples.

804
00:52:22,400 --> 00:52:24,607
Yeah, they got my hair
a bit wrong, though, didn't they?

805
00:52:24,960 --> 00:52:26,325
You don't have any hair!

806
00:52:26,920 --> 00:52:28,081
I have invisible hair.

807
00:52:28,960 --> 00:52:30,803
Got a suggestion for you then.

808
00:52:31,120 --> 00:52:32,610
Oh, there's a novelty.

809
00:52:33,200 --> 00:52:34,406
Don't die.

810
00:52:34,640 --> 00:52:35,926
Because if you do,

811
00:52:36,240 --> 00:52:39,449
I think everybody in the universe
might just go cold.

812
00:52:41,640 --> 00:52:43,369
Can't I ever have peace?

813
00:52:43,680 --> 00:52:45,250
Can't I rest?

814
00:52:49,480 --> 00:52:50,641
Of course you can.

815
00:52:50,960 --> 00:52:52,450
It's your choice.

816
00:52:52,600 --> 00:52:54,090
Only yours.

817
00:52:55,000 --> 00:52:56,240
We understand.

818
00:52:56,720 --> 00:52:58,006
No.

819
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:00,206
No, you don't.

820
00:53:01,560 --> 00:53:02,891
You're not even really here.

821
00:53:04,680 --> 00:53:06,125
You're just memories,

822
00:53:06,480 --> 00:53:07,720
held in glass.

823
00:53:09,280 --> 00:53:11,044
Do you know how many of you
I could fill?

824
00:53:11,480 --> 00:53:12,970
I would shatter you.

825
00:53:14,440 --> 00:53:16,681
My testimony would shatter all of you.

826
00:53:17,680 --> 00:53:19,091
A life this long,

827
00:53:19,160 --> 00:53:22,767
do you understand what it is?
It's a battlefield like this one.

828
00:53:24,680 --> 00:53:26,205
And it's empty.

829
00:53:28,400 --> 00:53:29,765
Because everyone else

830
00:53:30,360 --> 00:53:31,725
has fallen.

831
00:53:36,400 --> 00:53:39,085
Thank you, thank you both,

832
00:53:40,080 --> 00:53:42,048
for everything that
you were to me.

833
00:53:47,560 --> 00:53:49,449
What happens now,

834
00:53:50,280 --> 00:53:51,805
where I go

835
00:53:52,400 --> 00:53:53,481
now

836
00:53:55,200 --> 00:53:56,770
has to be alone.

837
00:54:08,040 --> 00:54:09,326
Cuddle.

838
00:54:24,840 --> 00:54:27,286
Time to leave the battlefield.

839
00:54:40,840 --> 00:54:45,084
Oh, there it is. Silly old universe.

840
00:54:46,720 --> 00:54:48,927
The more I save it,
the more it needs saving.

841
00:54:50,680 --> 00:54:52,011
It's a treadmill.

842
00:54:55,240 --> 00:54:59,245
Yes, yes, I know they'll get it
all wrong without me.

843
00:55:05,080 --> 00:55:08,527
Well, I suppose,
one more lifetime

844
00:55:09,440 --> 00:55:11,124
won't kill anyone.

845
00:55:14,240 --> 00:55:16,083
Well, except me.

846
00:55:24,760 --> 00:55:26,842
You wait a moment, Doctor.

847
00:55:27,680 --> 00:55:29,330
Let's get it right.

848
00:55:32,320 --> 00:55:34,482
I've got a few things
to say to you.

849
00:55:35,720 --> 00:55:37,609
Basic stuff first.

850
00:55:38,880 --> 00:55:41,690
Never be cruel, never be cowardly

851
00:55:42,600 --> 00:55:44,682
and never ever eat pears.

852
00:55:45,560 --> 00:55:47,050
Remember...

853
00:55:49,440 --> 00:55:51,886
Hate is always foolish.

854
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:56,324
Love is always wise.

855
00:56:03,720 --> 00:56:06,451
Always try to be nice,

856
00:56:06,520 --> 00:56:08,921
and never fail to be kind.

857
00:56:09,120 --> 00:56:11,441
Oh, and...

858
00:56:11,760 --> 00:56:13,842
You mustn't tell anyone your name.

859
00:56:16,640 --> 00:56:19,371
No one would understand it anyway.

860
00:56:21,960 --> 00:56:23,405
Except...

861
00:56:31,480 --> 00:56:34,450
Except children.

862
00:56:36,800 --> 00:56:38,609
Children can hear it

863
00:56:39,160 --> 00:56:40,844
sometimes

864
00:56:41,880 --> 00:56:44,281
if their hearts are in the right place

865
00:56:45,880 --> 00:56:48,087
and the stars are, too.

866
00:56:49,960 --> 00:56:52,281
Children can hear your name.

867
00:57:01,200 --> 00:57:03,168
But nobody else...

868
00:57:04,280 --> 00:57:06,123
Nobody else...

869
00:57:06,760 --> 00:57:08,091
Ever...

870
00:57:12,760 --> 00:57:14,603
Laugh hard.

871
00:57:15,920 --> 00:57:17,490
Run fast.

872
00:57:19,080 --> 00:57:20,570
Be kind.

873
00:57:26,880 --> 00:57:28,370
Doctor...

874
00:57:31,520 --> 00:57:33,124
I let you go.

875
00:58:32,880 --> 00:58:34,609
Oh, brilliant.

876
00:58:43,200 --> 00:58:45,771
Ah! Ah! Ah!

